result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both Operating A Motor Vehicle While Under The Influence-4TH Offense [Modifiers: General Alcohol Concentration Enhancer] and Operating With Prohibited Alcohol Concentration-4TH Offense [Modifiers: General Alcohol Concentration Enhancer]. The defendant was found guilty of Operating A Motor Vehicle While Under The Influence-4TH Offense [Modifiers: General Alcohol Concentration Enhancer] and the other charge, Operating With Prohibited Alcohol Concentration-4TH Offense [Modifiers: General Alcohol Concentration Enhancer] was dismissed by the court.

  • Steven John Camacho was found guilty of Operating A Motor Vehicle While Under The Influence-4TH Offense [Modifiers: General Alcohol Concentration Enhancer], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
